<HEAD>Colorado Developing Favorable Image In Japan, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese company's decision to build a
sake plant near here is a sign that Colorado is becoming well known
in Japan, a state economic development official says.
   ``I think there's a growing awareness of Colorado in the minds
of the Japanese citizens,'' said Susan Blansett, who is a business
development representative for the state's Office of Economic
Development.
   ``Colorado is gaining a favorable image. They're beginning to
equate it with the mountains, the clean water and environment in
general,'' she said.
   The Tatsuuma-Honke Brewing Co. Ltd., which brews a sake called
Hakushika, is purchasing an eight-acre parcel for the brewery in
the Coors Technology Center. It plans to break ground on a $7
million, 50,000-square-foot plant in April. When in operation, the
plant will employ about 50 people, including 30 from Colorado.
   The company began looking at Colorado sites about a year ago,
and signed the deal in September, said officials at Adolph Coors
Co., which is selling the land to Tatsuuma.
   Tatsuuma will compete with four other Japanese sake brewers for
the U.S. market, the officials say. Most of the companies are
building plants in California.
   Tatsuuma officials chose Colorado because they thought a plant
here would preserve a niche, Coors officials said.
   ``From the beginning, they really wanted to differentiate
themselves from their competitors,'' said Sandra Woods, Coors' vice
president for corporate real estate. ``The quality of water was the
most important thing to them.''
   Tatsuuma officials wanted ``the quality first, and a good
relationship with the community,'' added Alec Garbini, Coors'
director of corporate property development.
   Economic development officials believe Colorado eventually may
emerge as a bigger lure for Japanese tourism and investment than
the Canadian Rockies.
   Japanese companies already have purchased the Breckenridge and
Steamboat Springs ski resorts.
</TEXT>
