<DESCRIPT>  ECONOMY; EMPLOYMENT; RELATION; FAMILY; LIFESTYLE; JAPAN  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE U.S. economy is picking up again but the unemployment rate has reached 7
percent. Is America now heading down the same path as Western Europe, where
strong economies have long gone hand in hand with high unemployment?;
Economists don't think so. They say that when economies come out of
recessions, hiring at first is slow. Yet Japan, with the world's second
mightiest economy, has so far defied this trend, surviving economic ups and
downs with an unemployment rate of around 2 percent.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BUT IN JAPAN, EVERYONE HAS A JOB -- OR TWO  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Franz Schurmann is an editor for Pacific News Service and teaches history and
sociology at the University of California, Berkeley.
Commentary  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     During the mid-1950s, when I p6,6p3,6p,4p9,3p6,1p6 was a research student
in Japan, a farmer explained to me why no one had ever been unemployed in his
family and in so doing offered a clue as to how the country has achieved this
remarkable balancing act.;    He lived in an old farmhouse near Kyoto in an
area that was a typically Japanese mix of agricultural, industrial and
commercial. One son worked in a factory, another in an office. Both had
families and lived close by.;    The farmer grew rice and vegetables on a few
small plots of land. Some of the rice he brewed into high-quality sake, which
he sold in a small store next to his house.;    Parents and sons together
formed a single household economy. When farm prices were high, the farmer grew
as much rice and vegetables for the local market as he could. If rice prices
were low, he diverted more rice into sake-making and still came out all right.
But if both farming and brewing were not profitable, he needed his sons to
help him.;    The sons had jobs in the general economy, but they also made use
of a peculiarly Japanese institution to bring in a little more income.
Japanese workers have a basic job, but most also moonlight. They call it
arubaito, from the German word for work. The extra income usually goes for the
children or the parents.;    If work is slack in either the general or the
household economy, its members can switch over to the other. In Japan you can
be out of work without losing your job. You can then bring in substitute
income by doing more moonlighting, or helping out in the household economy of
your three-generational family.;    When foreigners think of the Japanese
economy, they think of mighty firms on the cutting edge of technological
innovation. Yet those firms are a superstructure that rests on a foundation of
millions of such household economies. The biggest firms still subcontract out
to family enterprises to provide their workers with package lunches and sake
for the parties that go on endlessly in Japanese economic life.;    Japanese
unemployment is so low because the general economy is in reality a vast social
fabric, and the social fabric is made up of millions of household economies.
In addition there are the many informal networks that make it possible to get
some arubaito from a friend in time of need.;    In Europe, on the other hand,
severe zoning restrictions make it difficult in many areas to start small
businesses. Houses are supposed to be residences, not places of business. A
long history of family dispersal has not only done away with the
three-generational family but is threatening the nuclear family as well. In
Europe, if you lose a job the only way to survive is to find another or get on
the dole.;    America's European roots have brought in the same dislike of
mixing home and business. Cottage industry is frowned on. Unlike arubaito,
moonlighting still has a shady feel about it.;    But in the 1980s, despite
deindustrialization, the United States had a low, un-European unemployment
rate of around 5 percent, and even lower in California where immigrant
influence is strong. Laid-off California automobile workers, according to the
Wall Street Journal, had an easier time adjusting through a flexible mix of
new jobs, moonlighting and expanding family income, than those in Michigan.;
 Economists and the media's business pages pretend that economics is mainly
numbers. Yet the Japanese, who are phenomenally good at the numbers, have long
known better. True, they're worried about their inflated real estate prices.
But what worries them far more is that their remarkable social fabric is
showing signs of looking like that of Europe and America.;    Japan's initial
success was due in good part to its technological borrowing from America. The
time has now come for the United States to consider borrowing some of the
social practices that have made Japan and other East Asian countries so
successful economically.  </TEXT>
