counterpart in 'Labor of Love'  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; THEATER; REVIEW; SEATTLE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  TALK ABOUT a trans-Pacific jambalaya!;   Take a Cajun accordion and some
Japanese drums, add some Hank Williams and haiku, simmer with crawfish and raw
fish, sprinkle in some controversial lines about trade and tradition, and
throw in a trans-Pacific love story.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MUSICAL ENTERTAINS IN TWO LANGUAGES
U.S.-JAPAN CONCERNS SERVED OVER RICE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Theater  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Then top it with rice -- some from Thibodeaux, La., and some from Sakiyama,
Japan.;   The boisterous, improbable result is "Labor of Love," the world's
first bilingual, bicultural, Cajun-Japanese musical comedy, which staged its
U.S. premiere before receptive crowds here in Seattle last weekend and plays
Friday through Sunday at the Cowell Theater at Fort Mason in San Francisco.;
Amid simmering tensions about trade that continue to dog the United States'
relationship with Japan, this two-hour rice-farmer musical doesn't avoid the
frictions that exist between the two industrial giants but reminds audiences
that rice growers in both nations face similar hurdles.;   On both sides of
the ocean, rice-harvesting doesn't pay without government support; on both
continents children want to abandon the traditional farms; in both nations,
rice-farming is laden with historical and cultural ties that are painfully
difficult to sever.;   'It's about cooperation';   "This play isn't about
rice," said Soichi Toda, president of Gekkeikan Sake U.S.A., the U.S. sponsor
of the tour, which is scheduled to barnstorm through rural rice-growing areas
of Arkansas and Louisiana. "It's about cooperation, cooperation between Japan
and the U.S.;   "Rice is a very political matter between Japan and the United
States," acknowledged Toda, whose firm last May opened a sake brewery in
Folsom, to distill sake from California-grown rice. "It is a matter than may
be resolved some day in the future. But the humanity of harvesting rice, the
human connection, is much more fundamental.";   The play, co-produced by the
One Reel of Seattle and Furusato Caravan of Tokyo, was warmly received earlier
this summer when it went on a 14-city tour of Japan, including stops in many
small, rural prefectures.;   "For many of those rural audiences, it is very
rare to see Americans," explained Katsuhiko Ishizuka, the Japanese co-director
of the play. "They harbor some uneasy feelings about Americans. But after a
while of watching the play, there was no longer a fear or distrust of these
American actors but an admiration and respect for Americans and their
country.";   A boisterous look at mores, manners and miscommunications, "Labor
of Love" focuses on the problems caused when Kenichi Suzuki, eldest son of a
rice-growing family in Japan, is invited to the rice-growing bayous of
Louisiana as part of an exchange program.;   There he learns about combines
and hot rods, and begins a friendship with Ali, one of the Thibodeaux
daughters. But difficulties begin when "Ken" writes an innocent note home to
his family, which is read by his parents as a sign that he is going to marry
the Thibodeaux daughter and bring her home to the farm.;   Thus begins a
home-exchange between the families, in which the subdued Suzuki family marvels
at the size of the Thibodeaux spread and the spiciness of creole cooking,
while the boisterous Thibodeaux clan wonders aloud about the squat toilets and
"paper doors" they encounter in the Suzuki home.;   While in the end, both
families agree that rice farming is an antiquated, poorly paid "Labor of
Love," the musical doesn't flinch from dredging up the seemingly perpetual
controversies between Americans and Japanese, including a fight among two
grandparents about Hiroshima and a confrontation over the fact that, though
Americans buy Japanese cars, Japanese consumers won't buy American rice.;
"The bottom line is that people don't need cars," a member of the Suzuki clan
says, "but they always need food.";   The unique creative collaboration behind
the play resulted from the work of One Reel executive producer Norman Langill,
who wanted to bring to the United States the kind of rural, traveling theater
that Furusato Caravan carries out in Japan -- shows about rural life produced
in front of rural people.;   After long discussions, the producers and show
writers toured apple orchards, wheat fields and tangerine farms before
settling on the rice harvest, which is associated with rich cultural legacies
on both sides of the Pacific.;   "When we were first working on this project,"
Ishizuka said, "we talked all about our differences in culture, language and
lifestyle. But after we spent time with the farmers in Louisiana and in Japan,
we discussed more and more the similarities.;   "This is really a play about
farmers' lives and how similar they are," he added, speaking through a
translator.;   U.S. version is a bit different;   Disconcerting as it may be
to see a blond, blue-eyed woman belting out a tune in Japanese, or a Japanese
singing about the joys of Cajun roux, the musical goes out of its way to
accommodate each language, with supratitles and translations built into the
staging. And, Ishizuka acknowledges, the play was transformed slightly for its
U.S. audiences because "Japanese humor wouldn't work in America.";   "The
jokes are hard to translate," he said, adding through his translator that he's
not eager to begin another Japanese-American collaboration.; Labor of Love;
When: 8 tonight-Saturday; Where: Cowell Theater, Fort Mason Center, San
Francisco; Tickets: $16. (408) 998-2277 or (415) 762-2277; Parking: Free
adjacent lot  </TEXT>
