<LEADPARA>  THERE comes a time in everyone's life -- especially after holiday shopping --
when the only solution to the vagaries of existence is finding a hot Japanese
bath for your body, a cold bottle of champagne for your soul and a hard futon
for your aching back.;   Which leads us to the Miyako Hotel in the heart of
San Francisco's Japantown, where all the above ingredients are not only
available, but part of the hotel's charm.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  A TASTE OF JAPAN IN THE HEART OF S.F.  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Someplace Special; Third in an occasional series  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     To be totally honest, the Miyako is a compromise between what you'd think a
Japanese hotel would be like and the realities of operating a hotel in the
westernized United States. At best, what you can do is get a whiff or two of
Japan, while realizing you're only a block or so from Geary Avenue.;   Still,
for those who are tired of what we might call "Corporate Hotel Decor," where
it's almost impossible to remember what city you're in, let alone what hotel,
the Miyako is a tasty change.;   In addition to its Japanese-style rooms,
however, the hotel has a number of Americanized rooms, most with private
saunas. These are probably for Japanese businessmen who are heartily tired of
futons and tatami mats and long for a huge American bed.;   Going to a
Japanese-style hotel and not staying in a Japanese-style room seems to defeat
the whole purpose, of course, although the American sauna suites are fine. We
chose one of the Japanese rooms, complete with sliding wooden doors and the
aforementioned futon and mats. The view out the window was splendid,
overlooking the hotel's tiny Japanese garden with a view of the Peace Pagoda
in the background.;   The bathtub, huge and deep, was still not quite
Japanese. But the water was hot and a supply of curious chemicals -- purported
to be restorative -- turned the water first yellow, then green. Whatever.
Amenities included two Japanese robes, just to put you in the Asian mood.;
The hotel cocktail bar was small and cozy; the dining room, spacious. Service
throughout, from valet parkers to waitresses in kimonos, was first class. We
do have to report that we found the Miyako's Japanese restaurant a tad
disappointing. The salmon teriyaki was bland, the prawn and vegetable tempura
a bit too oily. The sake was warm on arrival, but after it sat a bit, got
cold; no one offered to warm it back up. Ever had cold sake?;   Food aside,
most of the experience was just what the doctor -- and our aching backs --
ordered.; The Miyako Hotel; Where: 1625 Post St., San Francisco 94115; (800)
533-4567.; Rates: $100-$300; Location Z Z  Amenities Z Z Z Z; Hospitality Z Z
Z Z  Decor Z Z Z; Restaurant Z  Value Z Z Z; Rated on a scale of one to four
Zs, with four being tops.  </TEXT>
