<DESCRIPT>  OPINION; JAPAN; FUTURE; YEAR; FORECAST; UN  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE year's end in Japan begins in mid-November with the first sake-soaked
party to forget the old year. The parties-to-forget continue for weeks, segue
into parties to welcome the new year, and finally putter out around
mid-January, when the new year at last comes into focus.;   Japanese
policy-makers peering through December's alcohol fog are already focusing on a
new year more welcome than most. Japan's big chance to graduate from
diplomatic bridesmaid to diplomatic bride will come in 1992, changing the
international balance of power.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  JAPAN SCORES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Commentary; 1992: What Will Be; S.L. Bachman is a Mercury News editorial
writer.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     In short, Japan will finally win a permanent seat on the United Nations
Security Council.;   Japan has wanted a Security Council seat for a long time
to give it international diplomatic standing commensurate with its economic
might. For 46 years, council members have resisted changing the body's
membership for fear of permanently upsetting its balance of power.;   But the
dissolution of the Soviet Union will force the issue.;   Nevertheless, Japan
will have to fight an intense diplomatic battle to win a seat. For starters,
Tokyo will become the biggest contributor of foreign aid to pieces of the
former Soviet Union.;   Japan will have to press hard on other fronts as well,
mostly by spreading foreign aid generously around the world. Prime Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa will also oversee several peacemaking efforts. His biggest
coup will be winning North Korea's agreement to abandon nuclear weapons
development in return for several billion yen in loans, trade guarantees and
technical assistance.;   The prime minister will also pull every political
string at his disposal to pass legislation allowing Japanese troops to serve
as U.N. peacekeeping forces.;   Miyazawa's biggest task, however, will be
winning a Security Council nod from the United States.;   After months of
heavy courtship, which will include opening Japan's market to imported rice
and conclusion of international trade talks, President Bush will give his
blessing to the new council seat for Japan.;   But Bush will be preoccupied
with getting re-elected. That means any action on the council seat decision
will come after Nov. 3, most likely a week or two later, just in time for the
forget-the-year parties, giving Japanese policy-makers several weeks of sake
drinking before they have to focus on the responsibilities of diplomatic
married life.  </TEXT>
