<LEADPARA>  Q I had my girlfriend's name tattooed on my arm; the only trouble is that
she's not my girlfriend anymore. So I either have to find a girlfriend with
the same name or get the tattoo removed. Which is easier?; -- John, Dundalk,
Md.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PEEL OFF THAT TATTOO AT DOCTOR'S OFFICE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Health &amp; Fitness
Family Practice
Neil Solomon is a Maryland author and practicing physician with special
expertise in diet and weight control.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  A I'm not going to speculate about your ability to attract girlfriends, but I
can provide some information about tattoo removal. Although there are several
methods, the skin cannot be returned to its original condition.;    If time is
a factor, a chemical peel may be your best choice. It takes only a couple of
minutes to apply, does not require anesthesia and can be performed on an
outpatient basis. The treatment results in the formation of a scab, which
eventually falls off.;    "As with all of the other methods of removing
tattoos, chemical peel leaves its own mark: . . . a scar that's lighter or
darker, and often of a different texture, than the skin that surrounds it,"
says Dr. Michael Marschall.;    Used traditionally to remove fine facial
wrinkles, a chemical peel burns away the top layer of skin. However, unlike
the phenol solution used for many face peels, the trichloroacetic acid used by
Marschall is not absorbed by the body and does not pose a risk of heart
problems.;    Tattoos also can be removed by cutting them out, "sanding" them
off through a process called dermabrasion, or vaporizing the pigment with a
laser.;    Q When I was in Japan with the Army, I tried sake and found that I
liked it. How does the amount of alcohol in sake compare with the amount in
wine?; -- Len, Camden, N.J.; A Sake is made from rice. Its alcohol content is
about 16 percent, compared with an alcohol content of about 11 percent to 14
percent for wine  </TEXT>
