<LEADPARA>  In 18th- and 19th-century England, beer sales were governed by the system of
the Tied House and the Free House. A Tied House was a pub owned by a brewery,
which sold only the beer made by its owners. A Free House was a privately
owned pub that purchased ale from a variety of breweries.;   Now, England's
tradition has come to San Jose with the recently opened Tied House Cafe and
Brewery, the third establishment by the same name in the Bay Area. The first
opened in Mountain View in 1987; the second opened earlier this year in
Alameda.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  East Extra Part 2  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  TIED HOUSE CAFE AND BREWERY A LITTLE UNEVEN  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Restaurants; Extra's reviewers evaluate restaurants as typical consumers. They
visit area restaurants as unannounced, paying customers.; Additional
information attached to the end of this article; Also ran in EX4/  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     A lunch and a dinner visit to the San Jose Tied House made it clear the
word already is out. It's new. It's popular. It's crowded. But with time, that
will probably level out.;   Although the line to get in seemed long, we were
seated quickly both times. At dinner, the large L-shaped bar and surrounding
area was standing room only. During both visits, the restaurant and outdoor
patio were bustling.;   The lunch and dinner menus are almost identical, with
the exception of marginal price increases for many of the items. There aren't
a lot of different entrees, but the selections go well with the beers that are
brewed on-site.;   Entrees include English-style fish 'n' chips, a sausage,
black bean and rice plate, and beer-mustard chicken breast. There is a wide
selection of appetizers, including shrimp steamed in beer, oyster shooters,
Cajun spice onion rings and blackened catfish strips. The cost of an entree
ranges from $6.50 to $14.95; appetizers range from $1.95 to $6.95.;   To
accompany your meal, you can choose a pale, amber or dark brew. A handful of
specialty brews are listed on blackboards throughout the restaurant. Beers are
available in half-pint and pint sizes or by the pitcher, or you can get the
original triple sampler and taste all three varieties. We sampled all but the
dark brew. And between the pale and the amber, I preferred the rich flavor of
the amber to the somewhat sweet taste of the pale.;   At lunch, my dining
companion and I both selected daily specials instead of ordering from the
standard menu. My companion enjoyed a large piece of yellow-fin tuna with
wasabi and soy sauce, saying it rivaled versions of the dish served at other
well-known downtown restaurants.;   I chose the house sandwich, a turkey and
ham roll-up with sprouts, tomatoes, mustard and mayonnaise. It was made in the
style of a burrito and was quite tasty, although the portion was smaller than
I anticipated. I also ordered a beer cheese appetizer, which our server said
was made from "all of the ends of the various cheeses" and then "mixed with
beer." It was a fine accompaniment to the exceptional brown and white bread.
The cheese was a bit pungent and had its own character, but it's definitely
something to try.;   For our dinner visit, we started out with black bean
nachos with fresh beer salsa, sour cream and jack and cheddar cheese. We were
surprised by a heaping plate of nachos that was more than the two of us could
handle. They were quite good, though neither of us could taste any hint of
beer in the salsa.;   My dining companion had the half slab of smoked barbecue
pork ribs with sweet sauce. They were served with fries and a barbecued red
onion wrapped in foil that was so tender it literally fell apart. The ribs
were very good, the sauce tangy and sweet and the portion more than adequate.;
  I again chose a special: the linguini primavera with a wine butter sauce and
a dinner salad (which does not come with any of the entrees) with bleu cheese
dressing. The dressing was thin and the usual chunks of bleu cheese were
noticeably missing. The linguini didn't compensate. It was bland, appearing
that only butter had been used to give the pasta and an unconventional mix of
vegetables just a hint of flavor. In addition to the expected carrots and
zucchini, the vegetables included a more unusual selection of cabbage, snow
peas and tomatoes. But the dish didn't meet my expectations.;   For desert, we
shared a chocolate mousse. It did little to round out my evening. I expected a
light mild mousse. Instead, I got a thick, dark mousse reminiscent of
chocolate fudge frosting. My companion, however, thought it was great -- but
he loves chocolate for the sake of chocolate.;   Overall, our lunch and dinner
experiences at Tied House were good, but perhaps time will bring a more
consistent quality to both the food and the service.; Tied House Cafe; and
Brewery; Where: 65 N. San Pedro Street, San Jose; When: Daily from 11 a.m. to
11 p.m. or later; Phone: (408) 295-BREW; Etc.: Cash, Visa, Mastercard, Diner's
Club, and Discover accepted. Metered and garage parking available nearby. Full
service bar and catering available.  </TEXT>
