<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 93 / Japan ready to end ban on rice imports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO, FRANCES WILLIAMS and DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO, GENEVA, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN has informally floated a proposal to lift its ban on rice imports
after a six-year moratorium period to 1999, according to trade negotiators
in Tokyo and Geneva.
In a second initiative late yesterday in Geneva, Japan is also offering to
harmonise at low levels its tariffs on non-ferrous metals, and cut by at
least 50 per cent its tariff peaks on a further 150 textile items.
A US trade negotiator described the initiative, unveiled during a full
meeting of Uruguay round participants aimed at taking stock of progress in
negotiations, as 'an additional concrete step' towards successful completion
of the Uruguay round of world trade talks.
The rice proposal, which was made unofficially during intensive bilateral
discussions on reform of farm trade with the US in Geneva, will only be
presented formally once the US and the EC settle differences on farm
subsidies and market access for agriculture products, an official said.
Under the plan, Japan will accept tarification of rice after a six-year
grace period, during which a minimum access level of at least 5 per cent of
its domestic rice consumption will be imported, an official said.
Mr Joe O'Mara, special US trade negotiator for agriculture, said in Geneva
that the two sides were trying to conclude the talks by November 1, ahead of
the December 15 deadline to complete the Uruguay Round negotiations.
Formal headway may yet be frustrated by the refusal of the EC so far to
enter any negotiations on opening its market to more farm imports.
This is largely due to French efforts to review a US-EC agreement on
Europe's subsidised farm exports, and even to withdraw the farm sector from
the Uruguay Round agenda.
News of progress towards a compromise on ending Japan's ban on rice imports
is likely to isolate France on the issue of farm trade, and put fresh
pressure on the EC to negotiate tariff cuts in the sector.
Negotiators in Geneva were quick to note yesterday that France's domestic
problems in selling a farm package were no greater than those of the
Japanese government; if Japan compromises on rice imports for the sake of a
wider agreement, pressure would increase on France to do the same.
A trade negotiator in Geneva said the Japanese initiative on non-ferrous
metals amounted to 'one more area where the rest of the Quad (which groups
the US, Japan, Canada and the EC) are in agreement, and the EC stands in the
way of a package.' Both Canada and the US want tariffs on non-ferrous metals
entirely eliminated.
The welcome for Japan's initiatives was not extended to a new EC market
access package ready to be tabled next week. This proposes adding toys and
vegetable oils to the list of items on which tariffs will be cut to zero,
and cuts average tariffs by about 33 per cent, against a previous offer of
some 23 per cent. One US official, noting that the current US offer achieved
cuts averaging 38-42 per cent, said the EC offer 'hardly passes the laugh
test'.
Meanwhile, in Tokyo, news of the Japanese rice proposal yesterday caused
embarrassment for Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, the prime minister, and his
government, which was quick to deny reports of a tarification accord.
Mr Masayoshi Takemura, chief cabinet secretary, reiterated that Japan had no
intention of subjecting rice to the tarification scheme proposed by the
Gatt.
Meanwhile leaders of the Socialist party, the largest in Mr Hosokawa's
coalition, who staunchly oppose the opening of the rice market, threatened
to pull the party out of the coalition if the cabinet accepted tarification.
</TEXT>
