<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUL 92 / Tokyo shares pulled down by debt fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Tokyo stock market fell yesterday to its lowest level since April 1986,
as doubts spread about the health of the economy following release of a
gloomy Bank of Japan quarterly forecast.
The Nikkei stock average slipped 2.9 per cent to close at 15,541.95. Prices
continued to fall early today, with the Nikkei down more than 150 points in
initial trading.
The Bank of Japan said yesterday that it was closely watching the
restructuring of troubled non-bank financial institutions, whose
difficulties have been heightened by the renewed weakness of Tokyo stock
prices.
Mr Yasushi Mieno, the central bank governor, said the financial system was
secure in spite of difficulties facing non-bank lending institutions, which
fuelled the stock and property price spiral of the late 1980s, but now have
fast accumulating bad debts.
He said non-banks and other institutions should not necessarily support all
of their troubled borrowers, and suggested that financial institutions
restructuring their operations should maker further changes to ensure their
profitability.
Mr Mieno's comments made clear the central bank has revised its outlook on
the economy, and that a recovery expected in the autumn will come later. He
pointed to decelerating consumer demand as an important reason for delays in
adjustment of inventories. Concerned that the stock market decline could
prompt further falls in the next few days, Mr Sakae Kudo, chairman of the
Japan Securities Dealers' Association, said the market correction must be
close to completion.
But Mr Sakae said stock prices were being weighed down by concerns about the
domestic economy and suggested the Bank of Japan reduce the official
discount rate from the present 3.75 per cent.
The ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) is growing in confidence that it
will win a larger than generally predicted share of seats contested in an
election on Sunday for half the upper house of parliament.
Opposition parties admitted their campaigns had been flawed. Polls suggest
the LDP could take about 70 of the 127 seats, instead of the 60 or fewer
seats forecast when the campaign began. If so, the party and two coalition
partners, Komeito and the Democratic Socialist Party, will consolidate their
control over the upper house.
